# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-on-chip
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] In data communications, **flow control** is the process of managing the rate of data transmission between two nodes to prevent a fast sender from overwhelming a slow receiver.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Flow control should be distinguished from congestion control, which is used for controlling the flow of data when congestion has actually occurred.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Flow control mechanisms can be classified by whether or not the receiving node sends feedback to the sending node.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Flow control is important because it is possible for a sending computer to transmit information at a faster rate than the destination computer can receive and process it.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] This can happen if the receiving computers have a heavy traffic load in comparison to the sending computer, or if the receiving computer has less processing power than the sending computer.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Stop-and-wait flow control is the simplest form of flow control.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] In this method the message is broken into multiple frames, and the receiver indicates its readiness to receive a frame of data.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The sender waits for a receipt acknowledgement (ACK) after every frame for a specified time (called a time out).
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The receiver sends the ACK to let the sender know that the frame of data was received correctly.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The sender will then send the next frame only after the ACK.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Sender waits to receive ACK within time out.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] **Receiver:** Transmits acknowledgement (ACK) as it receives a frame.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Go to step 1 when ACK is received, or time out is hit.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] If a frame or ACK is lost during transmission then the frame is re-transmitted.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] This re-transmission process is known as ARQ (automatic repeat request).
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The problem with Stop-and-wait is that only one frame can be transmitted at a time, and that often leads to inefficient transmission, because until the sender receives the ACK it cannot transmit any new packet.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] During this time both the sender and the channel are unutilised.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The only advantage of this method of flow control is its simplicity.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The sender needs to wait for the ACK after every frame it transmits.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] This is a source of inefficiency, and is particularly bad when the propagation delay is much longer than the transmission delay.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Stop and wait can also create inefficiencies when sending longer transmissions.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] When longer transmissions are sent there is more likely chance for error in this protocol.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] If the messages are short the errors are more likely to be detected early.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] More inefficiency is created when single messages are broken into separate frames because it makes the transmission longer.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] A method of flow control in which a receiver gives a transmitter permission to transmit data until a window is full.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] When the window is full, the transmitter must stop transmitting until the receiver advertises a larger window.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Sliding-window flow control is best utilized when the buffer size is limited and pre-established.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] During a typical communication between a sender and a receiver the receiver allocates buffer space for *n* frames (*n* is the buffer size in frames).
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The sender can send and the receiver can accept *n* frames without having to wait for an acknowledgement.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] A sequence number is assigned to frames in order to help keep track of those frames which did receive an acknowledgement.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The receiver acknowledges a frame by sending an acknowledgement that includes the sequence number of the next frame expected.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] This acknowledgement announces that the receiver is ready to receive n frames, beginning with the number specified.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Both the sender and receiver maintain what is called a window.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The size of the window is less than or equal to the buffer size.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Sliding window flow control has far better performance than stop-and-wait flow control.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] For example, in a wireless environment if data rates are low and noise level is very high, waiting for an acknowledgement for every packet that is transferred is not very feasible.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Therefore, transferring data as a bulk would yield a better performance in terms of higher throughput.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Sliding window flow control is a point to point protocol assuming that no other entity tries to communicate until the current data transfer is complete.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The window maintained by the sender indicates which frames it can send.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The sender sends all the frames in the window and waits for an acknowledgement (as opposed to acknowledging after every frame).
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The sender then shifts the window to the corresponding sequence number, thus indicating that frames within the window starting from the current sequence number can be sent.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] An automatic repeat request (ARQ) algorithm, used for error correction, in which a negative acknowledgement (NACK) causes retransmission of the word in error as well as the next N–1 words.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The value of N is usually chosen such that the time taken to transmit the N words is less than the round trip delay from transmitter to receiver and back again.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Therefore, a buffer is not needed at the receiver.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The normalized propagation delay (a) = propagation time (Tp)⁄transmission time (Tt), where Tp = length (L) over propagation velocity (V) and Tt = bitrate (r) over framerate (F).
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] To get the utilization you must define a window size (N).
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] If N is greater than or equal to 2a + 1 then the utilization is 1 (full utilization) for the transmission channel.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] If it is less than 2a + 1 then the equation N⁄1+2a must be used to compute utilization.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] This section is geared towards the idea of comparing *stop-and-wait*, *sliding window* with the subsets of *go back N* and *selective repeat*.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] We define throughput T as the average number of blocks communicated per transmitted block.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] It is more convenient to calculate the average number of transmissions necessary to communicate a block, a quantity we denote by 0, and then to determine T from the equation $T={\frac {1}{b}}$ .
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The transmission rate may be controlled because of network or DTE requirements.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Transmit flow control can occur independently in the two directions of data transfer, thus permitting the transfer rates in one direction to be different from the transfer rates in the other direction.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] An example of hardware flow control is a half-duplex radio modem to computer interface.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] In this case, the controlling software in the modem and computer may be written to give priority to incoming radio signals such that outgoing data from the computer is paused by lowering CTS if the modem detects a reception.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Conversely, XON / XOFF is usually referred to as software flow control, and uses the characters 0x11 and 0x13 hexadecimal.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The open-loop flow control mechanism is characterized by having no feedback between the receiver and the transmitter.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] This simple means of control is widely used.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The allocation of resources must be a "prior reservation" or "hop-to-hop" type.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Open-loop flow control has inherent problems with maximizing the utilization of network resources.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Resource allocation is made at connection setup using a CAC (*connection admission control*) and this allocation is made using information that is already "old news" during the lifetime of the connection.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Often there is an over-allocation of resources and reserved but unused capacities are wasted.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Open-loop flow control is used by ATM in its CBR, VBR and UBR services (see traffic contract and congestion control).
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Open-loop flow control incorporates two controls; the controller and a regulator.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The regulator is able to alter the input variable in response to the signal from the controller.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] An open-loop system has no feedback or feed forward mechanism, so the input and output signals are not directly related and there is increased traffic variability.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] There is also a lower arrival rate in such system and a higher loss rate.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] In an open control system, the controllers can operate the regulators at regular intervals, but there is no assurance that the output variable can be maintained at the desired level.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] While it may be cheaper to use this model, the open-loop model can be unstable.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The closed-loop flow control mechanism is characterized by the ability of the network to report pending network congestion back to the transmitter.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] This information is then used by the transmitter in various ways to adapt its activity to existing network conditions.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Closed-loop flow control is used by ABR (see traffic contract and congestion control).
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Transmit flow control described above is a form of closed-loop flow control.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] This system incorporates all the basic control elements, such as, the sensor, transmitter, controller and the regulator.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The sensor is used to capture a process variable.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The process variable is sent to a transmitter which translates the variable to the controller.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The controller examines the information with respect to a desired value and initiates a correction action if required.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The controller then communicates to the regulator what action is needed to ensure that the output variable value is matching the desired value.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Therefore, there is a high degree of assurance that the output variable can be maintained at the desired level.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] A feedback closed-loop system has a feed-back mechanism that directly relates the input and output signals.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The feed-back mechanism monitors the output variable and determines if additional correction is required.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The output variable value that is fed backward is used to initiate that corrective action on a regulator.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] Most control loops in the industry are of the feedback type.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] In a feed-forward closed loop system, the measured process variable is an input variable.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The measured signal is then used in the same fashion as in a feedback system.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The closed-loop model produces lower loss rate and queuing delays, as well as it results in congestion-responsive traffic.
[src:network-on-chip/flow-control-data] The closed-loop model is always stable, as the number of active lows is bounded.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In integrated circuits (ICs), **interconnects** are structures that connect two or more circuit elements (such as transistors) together electrically.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The design and layout of interconnects on an IC is vital to its proper function, performance, power efficiency, reliability, and fabrication yield.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The material interconnects are made from depends on many factors.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Chemical and mechanical compatibility with the semiconductor substrate and the dielectric between the levels of interconnect is necessary, otherwise barrier layers are needed.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Suitability for fabrication is also required; some chemistries and processes prevent the integration of materials and unit processes into a larger technology (recipe) for IC fabrication.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In fabrication, interconnects are formed during the back-end-of-line (BEOL) after the fabrication of the transistors on the substrate.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Interconnects are classified as *local* or *global* interconnects depending on the signal propagation distance it is able to support.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The width and thickness of the interconnect, as well as the material from which it is made, are some of the significant factors that determine the distance a signal may propagate.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Local interconnects connect circuit elements that are very close together, such as transistors separated by ten or so other contiguously laid out transistors.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Global interconnects can transmit further, such as over large-area sub-circuits.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Consequently, local interconnects may be formed from materials with relatively high electrical resistivity such as polycrystalline silicon (sometimes silicided to extend its range) or tungsten.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] To extend the distance an interconnect may reach, various circuits such as buffers or restorers may be inserted at various points along a long interconnect.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The geometric properties of an interconnect are width, thickness, spacing (the distance between an interconnect and another on the same level), pitch (the sum of the width and spacing), and aspect ratio, or AR, (the thickness divided by width).
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The width, spacing, AR, and ultimately, pitch, are constrained in their minimum and maximum values by design rules that ensure the interconnect (and thus the IC) can be fabricated by the selected technology with a reasonable yield.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Width is constrained to ensure minimum width interconnects do not suffer breaks, and maximum width interconnects can be planarized by chemical mechanical polishing (CMP).
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Spacing is constrained to ensure adjacent interconnects can be fabricated without any conductive material bridging.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Thickness is determined solely by the technology, and the aspect ratio, by the chosen width and set thickness.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In technologies that support multiple levels of interconnects, each group of contiguous levels, or each level, has its own set of design rules.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Before the introduction of CMP for planarizing IC layers, interconnects had design rules that specified larger minimum widths and spaces than the lower level to ensure that the underlying layer's rough topology did not cause breaks in the interconnect formed on top.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The introduction of CMP has made finer geometries possible.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In technologies that form interconnect structures with conventional processes, the AR is limited to ensure that the etch creating the interconnect, and the dielectric deposition that fills the voids in between interconnects with dielectric, can be done successfully.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In those that form interconnect structures with damascene processes, the AR must permit successful etch of the trenches, deposition of the barrier metal (if needed) and interconnect material.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Interconnect layout are further restrained by design rules that apply to collections of interconnects.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] For a given area, technologies that rely on CMP have *density rules* to ensure the whole IC has an acceptable variation in interconnect density.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] This is because the rate at which CMP removes material depends on the material's properties, and great variations in interconnect density can result in large areas of dielectric which can dish, resulting in poor planarity.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] To maintain acceptable density, *dummy interconnects* (or *dummy wires*) are inserted into regions with spare interconnect density.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Historically, interconnects were routed in straight lines, and could change direction by using sections aligned 45° away from the direction of travel.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] As IC structure geometries became smaller, to obtain acceptable yields, restrictions were imposed on interconnect direction.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Initially, only global interconnects were subject to restrictions; were made to run in straight lines aligned east–west or north–south.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] To allow easy routing, alternate levels of interconnect ran in the same alignment, so that changes in direction were achieved by connecting to a lower or upper level of interconnect though a via.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Local interconnects, especially the lowest level (usually polysilicon) could assume a more arbitrary combination of routing options to attain the a higher packing density.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In silicon ICs, the most commonly used semiconductor in ICs, the first interconnects were made of aluminum.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Aluminum was an ideal material for interconnects due to its ease of deposition and good adherence to silicon and silicon dioxide.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Al interconnects are deposited by physical vapor deposition or chemical vapor deposition methods.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] They were originally patterned by wet etching, and later by various dry etching techniques.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Initially, pure aluminum was used but by the 1970s, substrate compatibility, junction spiking and reliability concerns (mostly concerning electromigration) forced the use of aluminum-based alloys containing silicon, copper, or both.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] By the late 1990s, the high resistivity of aluminum, coupled with the narrow widths of the interconnect structures forced by continuous feature size downscaling, resulted in prohibitively high resistance in interconnect structures.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] This forced aluminum's replacement by copper interconnects.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In gallium arsenide (GaAs) ICs, which have been mainly used in application domains (e.g. monolithic microwave ICs) different to those of silicon, the predominant material used for interconnects is gold.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] To reduce the delay penalty caused by parasitic capacitance, the dielectric material used to insulate adjacent interconnects, and interconnects on different levels (the inter-level dielectric [ILD]), should have a dielectric constant that is as close to 1 as possible.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] A class of such materials, Low-κ dielectrics, were introduced during the late 1990s and early 2000s for this purpose.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] As of January 2019, the most advanced materials reduce the dielectric constant to very low levels through highly porous structures, or through the creation of substantial air or vacuum pockets (air gap dielectric).
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] These materials often have low mechanical strength and are restricted to the lowest level or levels of interconnect as a result.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The high density of interconnects at the lower levels, along with the minimal spacing, helps support the upper layers.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Intel introduced air-gap dielectric in its 14 nm technology in 2014.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] ICs with complex circuits require multiple levels of interconnect to form circuits that have minimal area.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] As of 2018, the most complex ICs may have over 15 layers of interconnect.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Each level of interconnect is separated from each other by a layer of dielectric.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] To make vertical connections between interconnects on different levels, vias are used.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The top-most layers of a chip have the thickest and widest and most widely separated metal layers, which make the wires on those layers have the least resistance and smallest RC time constant, so they are used for power and clock distribution networks.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The bottom-most metal layers of the chip, closest to the transistors, have thin, narrow, tightly-packed wires, used only for local interconnect.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] Adding layers can potentially improve performance, but adding layers also reduces yield and increases manufacturing costs.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] ICs with a single metal layer typically use the polysilicon layer to "jump across" when one signal needs to cross another signal.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] The process used to form DRAM capacitors creates a rough and hilly surface, which makes it difficult to add metal interconnect layers and still maintain good yield.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In 1998, state-of-the-art DRAM processes had four metal layers, while state-of-the-art logic processes had seven metal layers.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In 2002, five or six layers of metal interconnect was common.
[src:network-on-chip/interconnect-integrated-circuits] In 2009, 1 Gbit DRAM typically had three layers of metal interconnect; tungsten for the first layer and aluminum for the upper layers.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] A **network on a chip**, or **network on chip** (**NoC** /ˌɛnˌoʊˈsiː/ *en-oh-SEE* or /nɒk/ *knock*), is a network-based communications subsystem on an integrated circuit ("chip"), most typically between modules in a system on chip (SoC).
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The modules on the IC are typically semiconductor IP cores schematizing various functions of the computer system, and are designed to be modular in the sense of network science.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The network on chip is a router-based packet switching network between SoC modules.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] NoC technology applies the theory and methods of computer networking to on-chip communication and brings notable improvements over conventional bus and crossbar communication architectures.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Networks on chip come in many network topologies, many of which are still experimental as of 2018.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] In the 2000s, researchers had started to propose a type of on-chip interconnection in the form of packet switching networks in order to address the scalability issues of bus-based design.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Preceding researches proposed the design that routes data packets instead of routing the wires.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Then, the concept of "networks on chip" was proposed in 2002.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] NoCs improve the scalability of systems-on-chip and the power efficiency of complex SoCs compared to other communication subsystem designs.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] They are an emerging technology, with projections for large growth in the near future as multicore computer architectures become more common.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] NoCs can span synchronous and asynchronous clock domains, known as clock domain crossing, or use unclocked asynchronous logic.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] NoCs support globally asynchronous, locally synchronous electronics architectures, allowing each processor core or functional unit on a system on chip to have its own clock domain.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] NoC architectures typically model sparse small-world networks (SWNs) and scale-free networks (SFNs) to limit the number, length, area and power consumption of interconnection wires and point-to-point connections.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The topology determines the physical layout and connections between nodes and channels.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The message traverses hops, and each hop's channel length depends on the topology.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The topology significantly influences both latency and power consumption.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Furthermore, since the topology determines the number of alternative paths between nodes, it affects the network traffic distribution, and hence the network bandwidth and performance achieved.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Traditionally, ICs have been designed with dedicated point-to-point connections, with one wire dedicated to each signal.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] This results in a dense network topology.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] For large designs, in particular, this has several limitations from a physical design viewpoint.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] It requires power quadratic in the number of interconnections.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The wires occupy much of the area of the chip, and in nanometer CMOS technology, interconnects dominate both performance and dynamic power dissipation, as signal propagation in wires across the chip requires multiple clock cycles.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] This also allows more parasitic capacitance, resistance and inductance to accrue on the circuit.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] (See Rent's rule for a discussion of wiring requirements for point-to-point connections).
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Sparsity and locality of interconnections in the communications subsystem yield several improvements over traditional bus-based and crossbar-based systems.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The wires in the links of the network-on-chip are shared by many signals.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] A high level of parallelism is achieved, because all data links in the NoC can operate simultaneously on different data packets.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Therefore, as the complexity of integrated systems keeps growing, a NoC provides enhanced performance (such as throughput) and scalability in comparison with previous communication architectures (e.g., dedicated point-to-point signal wires, shared buses, or segmented buses with bridges).
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The algorithms must be designed in such a way that they offer large parallelism and can hence utilize the potential of NoC.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Some researchers think that NoCs need to support quality of service (QoS), namely achieve the various requirements in terms of throughput, end-to-end delays, fairness, and deadlines.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Real-time computation, including audio and video playback, is one reason for providing QoS support.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] However, current system implementations like VxWorks, RTLinux or QNX are able to achieve sub-millisecond real-time computing without special hardware.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Another motivation for NoC-level quality of service (QoS) is to support multiple concurrent users sharing resources of a single chip multiprocessor in a public cloud computing infrastructure.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] In such instances, hardware QoS logic enables the service provider to make contractual guarantees on the level of service that a user receives, a feature that may be deemed desirable by some corporate or government clients.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Many challenging research problems remain to be solved at all levels, from the physical link level through the network level, and all the way up to the system architecture and application software.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The first dedicated research symposium on networks on chip was held at Princeton University, in May 2007.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The second IEEE International Symposium on Networks-on-Chip was held in April 2008 at Newcastle University.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Research has been conducted on integrated optical waveguides and devices comprising an optical network on a chip (ONoC).
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] The possible way to increasing the performance of NoC is use wireless communication channels between chiplets — named wireless network on chip (WiNoC).
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] In a multi-core system, connected by NoC, coherency messages and cache miss requests have to pass switches.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Accordingly, switches can be augmented with simple tracking and forwarding elements to detect which cache blocks will be requested in the future by which cores.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Then, the forwarding elements multicast any requested block to all the cores that may request the block in the future.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] NoC development and studies require comparing different proposals and options.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] NoC traffic patterns are under development to help such evaluations.
[src:network-on-chip/network-on-a-chip] Existing NoC benchmarks include NoCBench and MCSL NoC Traffic Patterns.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Network topology is the topological structure of a network and may be depicted physically or logically.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] It is an application of graph theory wherein communicating devices are modeled as nodes and the connections between the devices are modeled as links or lines between the nodes.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] **Physical topology** is the placement of the various components of a network (e.g., device location and cable installation), while **logical topology** illustrates how data flows within a network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Distances between nodes, physical interconnections, transmission rates, or signal types may differ between two different networks, yet their logical topologies may be identical.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A network's physical topology is a particular concern of the physical layer of the OSI model.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Examples of network topologies are found in local area networks (LAN), a common computer network installation.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Any given node in the LAN has one or more physical links to other devices in the network; graphically mapping these links results in a geometric shape that can be used to describe the physical topology of the network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A wide variety of physical topologies have been used in LANs, including ring, bus, mesh and star.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Conversely, mapping the data flow between the components determines the logical topology of the network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In comparison, Controller Area Networks, common in vehicles, are primarily distributed control system networks of one or more controllers interconnected with sensors and actuators over, invariably, a physical bus topology.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Two basic categories of network topologies exist: physical topologies and logical topologies.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The transmission medium layout used to link devices is the physical topology of the network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] For conductive or fiber optical mediums, this refers to the layout of cabling, the locations of nodes, and the links between the nodes and the cabling.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The physical topology of a network is determined by the capabilities of the network access devices and media, the level of control or fault tolerance desired, and the cost associated with cabling or telecommunication circuits.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In contrast, logical topology is the way that the signals act on the network media, or the way that the data passes through the network from one device to the next without regard to the physical interconnection of the devices.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A network's logical topology is not necessarily the same as its physical topology.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] For example, the original twisted pair Ethernet using repeater hubs was a logical bus topology carried on a physical star topology.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Token Ring is a logical ring topology, but is wired as a physical star from the media access unit.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Logical topologies are often closely associated with media access control methods and protocols.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Some networks are able to dynamically change their logical topology through configuration changes to their routers and switches.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The transmission media (often referred to in the literature as the *physical media*) used to link devices to form a computer network include electrical cables (Ethernet, HomePNA, power line communication, G.hn), optical fiber (fiber-optic communication), and radio waves (wireless networking).
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In the OSI model, these are defined at layers 1 and 2 — the physical layer and the data link layer.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A widely adopted *family* of transmission media used in local area network (LAN) technology is collectively known as Ethernet.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The media and protocol standards that enable communication between networked devices over Ethernet are defined by IEEE 802.3.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Ethernet transmits data over both copper and fiber cables.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Wireless LAN standards (e.g., those defined by IEEE 802.11) use radio waves, or others use infrared signals as a transmission medium.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Power line communication uses a building's power cabling to transmit data.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The orders of the following wired technologies are, roughly, from slowest to fastest transmission speed.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Price is a main factor distinguishing wired and wireless technology options in a business.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Wireless options command a price premium that can make purchasing wired computers, printers and other devices a financial benefit.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Before making the decision to purchase hard-wired technology products, a review of the restrictions and limitations of the selections is necessary.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Business and employee needs may override any cost considerations.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Both cases have a large round-trip delay time, which gives slow two-way communication, but does not prevent sending large amounts of information.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Network nodes are the points of connection of the transmission medium to transmitters and receivers of the electrical, optical, or radio signals carried in the medium.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Nodes may be associated with a computer, but certain types may have only a microcontroller at a node or possibly no programmable device at all.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In the simplest of serial arrangements, one RS-232 transmitter can be connected by a pair of wires to one receiver, forming two nodes on one link, or a point-to-point topology.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Some protocols permit a single node to only either transmit or receive (e.g., ARINC 429).
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Other protocols have nodes that can both transmit and receive into a single channel (e.g., CAN can have many transceivers connected to a single bus).
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A network interface controller (NIC) is computer hardware that provides a computer with the ability to access the transmission media, and has the ability to process low-level network information.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] For example, the NIC may have a connector for accepting a cable, or an aerial for wireless transmission and reception, and the associated circuitry.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The NIC responds to traffic addressed to a network address for either the NIC or the computer as a whole.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In Ethernet networks, each network interface controller has a unique Media Access Control (MAC) address—usually stored in the controller's permanent memory.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] To avoid address conflicts between network devices, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) maintains and administers MAC address uniqueness.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The size of an Ethernet MAC address is six octets.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The three most significant octets are reserved to identify NIC manufacturers.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] These manufacturers, using only their assigned prefixes, uniquely assign the three least-significant octets of every Ethernet interface they produce.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A repeater is an electronic device that receives a network signal, cleans it of unnecessary noise and regenerates it.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The signal may be reformed or retransmitted at a higher power level, to the other side of an obstruction, possibly using a different transmission medium, so that the signal can cover longer distances without degradation.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Commercial repeaters have extended RS-232 segments from 15 meters to over a kilometer.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In most twisted pair Ethernet configurations, repeaters are required for cable that runs longer than 100 meters.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] With fiber optics, repeaters can be tens or even hundreds of kilometers apart.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Repeaters work within the physical layer of the OSI model; that is, there is no end-to-end change in the physical protocol across the repeater, or repeater pair, even if a different physical layer may be used between the ends of the repeater, or repeater pair.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Repeaters require a small amount of time to regenerate the signal.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This can cause a propagation delay that affects network performance and may affect proper function.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] As a result, many network architectures limit the number of repeaters that can be used in a row, e.g., the Ethernet 5-4-3 rule.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A repeater with multiple ports is known as hub, an Ethernet hub in Ethernet networks, a USB hub in USB networks.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A network bridge connects and filters traffic between two network segments at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to form a single network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This breaks the network's collision domain but maintains a unified broadcast domain.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Network segmentation breaks down a large, congested network into an aggregation of smaller, more efficient networks.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A network switch is a device that forwards and filters OSI layer 2 datagrams (frames) between ports based on the destination MAC address in each frame.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A switch is distinct from a hub in that it only forwards the frames to the physical ports involved in the communication, rather than all ports connected.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] It can be thought of as a multi-port bridge.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] It learns to associate physical ports to MAC addresses by examining the source addresses of received frames.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] If an unknown destination is targeted, the switch broadcasts to all ports but the source.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Switches normally have numerous ports, facilitating a star topology for devices and cascading additional switches.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Multi-layer switches are capable of routing based on layer 3 addressing or additional logical levels.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The term *switch* is often used loosely to include devices such as routers and bridges, as well as devices that may distribute traffic based on load or based on application content (e.g., a Web URL identifier).
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A router is an internetworking device that forwards packets between networks by processing the routing information included in the packet or datagram (Internet protocol information from layer 3).
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The routing information is often processed in conjunction with the routing table (or forwarding table).
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A router uses its routing table to determine where to forward packets.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A destination in a routing table can include a black hole because data can go into it; however, no further processing is done for said data, i.e., the packets are dropped.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Modems (MOdulator-DEModulator) are used to connect network nodes via wire not originally designed for digital network traffic, or for wireless.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] To do this, one or more carrier signals are modulated by the digital signal to produce an analog signal that can be tailored to give the required properties for transmission.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Modems are commonly used for telephone lines, using a digital subscriber line technology.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A firewall is a network device for controlling network security and access rules.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Firewalls are typically configured to reject access requests from unrecognized sources while allowing actions from recognized ones.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The vital role firewalls play in network security grows in parallel with the constant increase in cyber attacks.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The study of network topology recognizes eight basic topologies: point-to-point, bus, star, ring or circular, mesh, tree, hybrid, or daisy chain.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The simplest topology with a dedicated link between two endpoints.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Easiest to understand of the variations of point-to-point topology is a point-to-point communication channel that appears, to the user, to be permanently associated with the two endpoints.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A child's tin can telephone is one example of a *physical dedicated* channel.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Using circuit-switching or packet-switching technologies, a point-to-point circuit can be set up dynamically and dropped when no longer needed.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Switched point-to-point topologies are the basic model of conventional telephony.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The value of a permanent point-to-point network is unimpeded communications between the two endpoints.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The value of an on-demand point-to-point connection is proportional to the number of potential pairs of subscribers and has been expressed as Metcalfe's Law.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Daisy chaining is accomplished by connecting each computer in series to the next.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] If a message is intended for a computer partway down the line, each system bounces it along in sequence until it reaches the destination.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A daisy-chained network can take two basic forms: linear and ring.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In local area networks using bus topology, each node is connected by interface connectors to a single central cable.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This is the 'bus', also referred to as the backbone, or trunk – all data transmission between nodes in the network is transmitted over this common transmission medium and is able to be received by all nodes in the network simultaneously.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A signal containing the address of the intended receiving machine travels from a source machine in both directions to all machines connected to the bus until it finds the intended recipient, which then accepts the data.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] If the machine address does not match the intended address for the data, the data portion of the signal is ignored.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Since the bus topology consists of only one wire, it is less expensive to implement than other topologies, but the savings are offset by the higher cost of managing the network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Additionally, since the network is dependent on the single cable, it can be the single point of failure of the network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In this topology, data being transferred may be accessed by any node.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In a linear bus network, all of the nodes of the network are connected to a common transmission medium, which has just two endpoints.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] When the electrical signal reaches the end of the bus, the signal is reflected back down the line, causing unwanted interference.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] To prevent this, the two endpoints of the bus are normally terminated with a device called a terminator.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In star topology (also called hub-and-spoke), every peripheral node (computer workstation or any other peripheral) is connected to a central node called a hub or switch.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The hub is the server and the peripherals are the clients.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The network does not necessarily have to resemble a star to be classified as a star network, but all of the peripheral nodes on the network must be connected to one central hub.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] All traffic that traverses the network passes through the central hub, which acts as a signal repeater.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The star topology is considered the easiest topology to design and implement.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] One advantage of the star topology is the simplicity of adding additional nodes.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The primary disadvantage of the star topology is that the hub represents a single point of failure.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Also, since all peripheral communication must flow through the central hub, the aggregate central bandwidth forms a network bottleneck for large clusters.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The extended star network topology extends a physical star topology by one or more repeaters between the central node and the peripheral (or 'spoke') nodes.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The repeaters are used to extend the maximum transmission distance of the physical layer, the point-to-point distance between the central node and the peripheral nodes.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Repeaters allow greater transmission distance, further than would be possible using just the transmitting power of the central node.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The use of repeaters can also overcome limitations from the standard upon which the physical layer is based.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A physical extended star topology in which repeaters are replaced with hubs or switches is a type of hybrid network topology and is referred to as a physical hierarchical star topology, although some texts make no distinction between the two topologies.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A physical hierarchical star topology can also be referred as a tier-star topology.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This topology differs from a tree topology in the way star networks are connected together.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A tier-star topology uses a central node, while a tree topology uses a central bus and can also be referred to as a star-bus network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A ring topology is a daisy chain in a closed loop.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Data travels around the ring in one direction.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] When one node sends data to another, the data passes through each intermediate node on the ring until it reaches its destination.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The intermediate nodes repeat (retransmit) the data to keep the signal strong.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Every node is a peer; there is no hierarchical relationship of clients and servers.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] If one node is unable to retransmit data, it severs communication between the nodes before and after it in the bus.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The value of fully meshed networks is proportional to the exponent of the number of subscribers, assuming that communicating groups of any two endpoints, up to and including all the endpoints, is approximated by Reed's Law.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In a *fully connected network*, all nodes are interconnected.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] (In graph theory this is called a complete graph.) The simplest fully connected network is a two-node network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A fully connected network doesn't need to use packet switching or broadcasting.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This makes it impractical for large networks.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This kind of topology does not trip and affect other nodes in the network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In a partially connected network, certain nodes are connected to exactly one other node, but some nodes are connected to two or more other nodes with a point-to-point link.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This makes it possible to make use of some of the redundancy of mesh topology that is physically fully connected, without the expense and complexity required for a connection between every node in the network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Hybrid topology is also known as hybrid network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Hybrid networks combine two or more topologies in such a way that the resulting network does not exhibit one of the standard topologies (e.g., bus, star, ring, etc.).
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] For example, a tree network (or *star-bus network*) is a hybrid topology in which star networks are interconnected via bus networks.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] However, a tree network connected to another tree network is still topologically a tree network, not a distinct network type.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A hybrid topology is always produced when two different basic network topologies are connected.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A *star-ring* network consists of two or more ring networks connected using a multistation access unit (MAU) as a centralized hub.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Two other hybrid network types are *hybrid mesh* and *hierarchical star*.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The **star topology** reduces the probability of a network failure by connecting all of the peripheral nodes (computers, etc.) to a central node.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] When the physical star topology is applied to a logical bus network such as Ethernet, this central node (traditionally a hub) rebroadcasts all transmissions received from any peripheral node to all peripheral nodes on the network, sometimes including the originating node.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] All peripheral nodes may thus communicate with all others by transmitting to, and receiving from, the central node only.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The failure of a transmission line linking any peripheral node to the central node will result in the isolation of that peripheral node from all others, but the remaining peripheral nodes will be unaffected.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] However, the disadvantage is that the failure of the central node will cause the failure of all of the peripheral nodes.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] If the central node is *passive*, the originating node must be able to tolerate the reception of an echo of its own transmission, delayed by the two-way round trip transmission time (i.e. to and from the central node) plus any delay generated in the central node.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] An *active* star network has an active central node that usually has the means to prevent echo-related problems.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] **hierarchical topology**) can be viewed as a collection of star networks arranged in a hierarchy.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This tree structure has individual peripheral nodes (e.g., leaves) which are required to transmit to and receive from one other node only and are not required to act as repeaters or regenerators.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Unlike the star network, the functionality of the central node may be distributed.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] As in the conventional star network, individual nodes may thus still be isolated from the network by a single-point failure of a transmission path to the node.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] If a link connecting a leaf fails, that leaf is isolated; if a connection to a non-leaf node fails, an entire section of the network becomes isolated from the rest.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] To alleviate the amount of network traffic that comes from broadcasting all signals to all nodes, more advanced central nodes were developed that are able to keep track of the identities of the nodes that are connected to the network.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] These network switches will *learn* the layout of the network by *listening* on each port during normal data transmission, examining the data packets and recording the address/identifier of each connected node and which port it is connected to in a lookup table held in memory.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This lookup table then allows future transmissions to be forwarded to the intended destination only.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Daisy chain topology is a way of connecting network nodes in a linear or ring structure.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] It is used to transmit messages from one node to the next until they reach the destination node.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A daisy chain network can have two types: linear and ring.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A linear daisy chain network is like an electrical series, where the first and last nodes are not connected.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A ring daisy chain network is where the first and last nodes are connected, forming a loop.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In a partially connected mesh topology, there are at least two nodes with two or more paths between them to provide redundant paths in case the link providing one of the paths fails.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Decentralization is often used to compensate for the single-point-failure disadvantage that is present when using a single device as a central node (e.g., in star and tree networks).
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A special kind of mesh, limiting the number of hops between two nodes, is a hypercube.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] The number of arbitrary forks in mesh networks makes them more difficult to design and implement, but their decentralized nature makes them very useful.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This is similar in some ways to a grid network, where a linear or ring topology is used to connect systems in multiple directions.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A multidimensional ring has a toroidal topology, for instance.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] A *fully connected network*, *complete topology*, or *full mesh topology* is a network topology in which there is a direct link between all pairs of nodes.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] In a fully connected network with n nodes, there are ${\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}\,$ direct links.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] Networks designed with this topology are usually very expensive to set up, but provide a high degree of reliability due to the multiple paths for data that are provided by the large number of redundant links between nodes.
[src:network-on-chip/network-topology] This topology is mostly seen in military applications.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] NUMA architectures logically follow in scaling from symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) architectures.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Techniques developed by these companies later featured in a variety of Unix-like operating systems, and to an extent in Windows NT.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] The first commercial implementation of a NUMA-based Unix system was the Symmetrical Multi Processing XPS-100 family of servers, designed by Dan Gielan of VAST Corporation for Honeywell Information Systems Italy.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Modern CPUs operate considerably faster than the main memory they use.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] In the early days of computing and data processing, the CPU generally ran slower than its own memory.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] The performance lines of processors and memory crossed in the 1960s with the advent of the first supercomputers.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Since then, CPUs increasingly have found themselves "starved for data" and forced to stall to wait for data to arrive from memory (e.g. for Von-Neumann architecture-based computers, see Von Neumann bottleneck).
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Many supercomputer designs of the 1980s and 1990s focused on providing high-speed memory access as opposed to faster processors, allowing the computers to work on large data sets at speeds other systems could not approach.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Limiting the number of memory accesses provided the key to extracting high performance from a modern computer.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] For commodity processors, this meant installing an ever-increasing amount of high-speed cache memory and using increasingly sophisticated algorithms to avoid cache misses.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] But the dramatic increase in size of both the operating systems and the applications that run on them has generally overwhelmed these cache-processing improvements.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Multi-processor systems without NUMA make the problem considerably worse.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Now a system can starve several processors at the same time, notably because only one processor can access the computer's memory at a time.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] NUMA attempts to address this problem by providing separate memory for each processor, avoiding the performance hit when several processors attempt to address the same memory.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] For problems involving spread data (common for servers and similar applications), NUMA can improve the performance over a single shared memory by a factor of roughly the number of processors (or separate memory banks).
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Another approach to addressing this problem is the multi-channel memory architecture, in which a linear increase in the number of memory channels increases the memory access concurrency linearly.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Of course, not all data ends up confined to a single task, which means that more than one processor may require the same data.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] To handle these cases, NUMA systems include additional hardware or software to move data between memory banks.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] This operation slows the processors attached to those banks, so the overall speed increase due to NUMA heavily depends on the nature of the running tasks.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] AMD implemented NUMA with its Opteron processor (2003), using HyperTransport.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Intel announced NUMA compatibility for its x86 and Itanium servers in late 2007 with its Nehalem and Tukwila CPUs.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Both Intel CPU families share a common chipset; the interconnection is called Intel QuickPath Interconnect (QPI), which provides extremely high bandwidth to enable high on-board scalability and was replaced by a new version called Intel UltraPath Interconnect with the release of Skylake (2017).
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Nearly all CPU architectures use a small amount of very fast non-shared memory known as cache to exploit locality of reference in memory accesses.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] With NUMA, maintaining cache coherence across shared memory has a significant overhead.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Although simpler to design and build, non-cache-coherent NUMA systems become prohibitively complex to program in the standard von Neumann architecture programming model.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Typically, ccNUMA uses inter-processor communication between cache controllers to keep a consistent memory image when more than one cache stores the same memory location.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] For this reason, ccNUMA may perform poorly when multiple processors attempt to access the same memory area in rapid succession.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Support for NUMA in operating systems attempts to reduce the frequency of this kind of access by allocating processors and memory in NUMA-friendly ways and by avoiding scheduling and locking algorithms that make NUMA-unfriendly accesses necessary.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Alternatively, cache coherency protocols such as the MESIF protocol attempt to reduce the communication required to maintain cache coherency.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Scalable Coherent Interface (SCI) is an IEEE standard defining a directory-based cache coherency protocol to avoid scalability limitations found in earlier multiprocessor systems.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] For example, SCI is used as the basis for the NumaConnect technology.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] One can view NUMA as a tightly coupled form of cluster computing.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] The addition of virtual memory paging to a cluster architecture can allow the implementation of NUMA entirely in software.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] However, the inter-node latency of software-based NUMA remains several orders of magnitude greater (slower) than that of hardware-based NUMA.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Since NUMA largely influences memory access performance, certain software optimizations are needed to allow scheduling threads and processes close to their in-memory data.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] As of 2011, ccNUMA systems are multiprocessor systems based on the AMD Opteron processor, which can be implemented without external logic, and the Intel Itanium processor, which requires the chipset to support NUMA.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Examples of ccNUMA-enabled chipsets are the SGI Shub (Super hub), the Intel E8870, the HP sx2000 (used in the Integrity and Superdome servers), and those found in NEC Itanium-based systems.
[src:network-on-chip/non-uniform-memory-access] Earlier ccNUMA systems such as those from Silicon Graphics were based on MIPS processors and the DEC Alpha 21364 (EV7) processor.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A **router** is a computer and networking device that forwards data packets between computer networks, including internetworks such as the global Internet.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Routers perform the *traffic directing* functions on the Internet.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A router is connected to two or more data lines from different IP networks.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] When a data packet comes in on a line, the router reads the network address information in the packet header to determine the ultimate destination.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Then, using information in its routing table or routing policy, it directs the packet to the next network on its journey.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A data packet is forwarded from one router to another through an internetwork until it reaches its destination node.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The most familiar type of IP routers are home and small office routers that forward IP packets between the home computers and the Internet.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] More sophisticated routers, such as enterprise routers, connect large business or ISP networks to powerful core routers that forward data at high speed along the optical fiber lines of the Internet backbone.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Routers can be built from standard computer parts but are mostly specialized purpose-built computers.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Early routers used software-based forwarding, running on a CPU.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] More sophisticated devices use application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) to increase performance or add advanced filtering and firewall functionality.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The concepts of a *switching node* using software and an *interface computer* were first proposed by Donald Davies in 1966 for the NPL network.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The same idea was conceived by Wesley Clark the following year for use in the ARPANET, which were named *Interface Message Processors* (IMPs).
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] These computers had fundamentally the same functionality as a router does today.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The idea for a router (called a *gateway* at the time) initially came about through an international group of computer networking researchers called the International Network Working Group (INWG).
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] These gateway devices were different from most previous packet switching schemes in two ways.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] First, they connected dissimilar kinds of networks, such as serial lines and local area networks.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Second, they were connectionless devices, which had no role in assuring that traffic was delivered reliably, leaving that function entirely to the hosts.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] This particular idea, the end-to-end principle, was contained in the work of Donald Davies.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The concept was explored in practice by various groups, with the intention to produce a working system for internetworking.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] There were three notable contemporaneous programs.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The first was an implementation directed by Louis Pouzin of the CYCLADES network, which was designed and developed during 1972-3.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The second was a program at Xerox PARC to explore new networking technologies, which produced the PARC Universal Packet system.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Some time after early 1974, the first Xerox routers became operational.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Due to corporate intellectual property concerns, it received little attention outside Xerox for years.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The third was a DARPA-initiated program, which began during 1973-4.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] This drew on the work of the other two programs, expanded significantly, and went on to create the TCP/IP architecture in use today.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] University College London (UCL) provided a gateway between British research groups and the ARPANET from 1973 until the late 1980s, latterly using SATNET.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The first true IP router was developed by Ginny Travers at BBN, as part of that DARPA-initiated effort, during 1975–1976.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] By the end of 1976, three PDP-11-based routers were in service in the experimental prototype Internet.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Mike Brecia, Ginny Travers, and Bob Hinden received the IEEE Internet Award for early IP routers in 2008.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The first multiprotocol routers were independently created by staff researchers at MIT and Stanford in 1981 and both were also based on PDP-11s.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Stanford's router program was led by William Yeager and MIT's by Noel Chiappa.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Virtually all networking now uses TCP/IP, but multiprotocol routers are still manufactured.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] They were important in the early stages of the growth of computer networking when protocols other than TCP/IP were in use.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Modern routers that handle both IPv4 and IPv6 are multiprotocol but are simpler devices than those that process AppleTalk, DECnet, IPX, and Xerox protocols.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] From the mid-1970s and in the 1980s, general-purpose minicomputers served as routers.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Modern high-speed routers are network processors or highly specialized computers with extra hardware acceleration added to speed both common routing functions, such as packet forwarding, and specialized functions such as IPsec encryption.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] There is substantial use of Linux and Unix software-based machines, running open source routing code, for research and other applications.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The Cisco IOS operating system was independently designed.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Major router operating systems, such as Junos and NX-OS, are extensively modified versions of Unix software.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] When multiple routers are used in interconnected networks, the routers can exchange information about destination addresses using a routing protocol.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Each router builds up a routing table, a list of routes, between two computer systems on the interconnected networks.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A router may have interfaces for multiple types of physical layer connections, such as copper cables, fiber optic, or wireless transmission.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] It can also support multiple network layer transmission standards.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Each network interface is used to enable data packets to be forwarded from one transmission system to another.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Routers may also be used to connect two or more logical groups of computer devices known as subnets, each with a unique network prefix.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Routers may provide connectivity within enterprises, between enterprises and the Internet, or between internet service providers' (ISPs') networks; they are also responsible for directing data between different networks.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The largest routers (such as the Cisco CRS-1 or Juniper PTX) interconnect the various ISPs, or may be used in large enterprise networks.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Smaller routers usually provide connectivity for typical home and office networks.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] All sizes of routers may be found inside enterprises.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The most powerful routers are usually found in ISPs, academic and research facilities.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Large businesses may also need more powerful routers to cope with ever-increasing demands of intranet data traffic.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A hierarchical internetworking model for interconnecting routers in large networks is in common use.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Some routers can connect to Data service units for T1 connections via serial ports.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The hierarchical internetworking model divides enterprise networks into three layers: core, distribution, and access.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Access routers, including small office/home office (SOHO) models, are located at home and customer sites such as branch offices that do not need hierarchical routing of their own.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Typically, they are optimized for low cost.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Some SOHO routers are capable of running alternative free Linux-based firmware like Tomato, OpenWrt, or DD-WRT.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Distribution routers aggregate traffic from multiple access routers.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Distribution routers are often responsible for enforcing quality of service across a wide area network (WAN), so they may have considerable memory installed, multiple WAN interface connections, and substantial onboard data processing routines.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] They may also provide connectivity to groups of file servers or other external networks.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] In enterprises, a core router may provide a collapsed backbone interconnecting the distribution tier routers from multiple buildings of a campus, or large enterprise locations.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] They tend to be optimized for high bandwidth but lack some of the features of edge routers.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] External networks must be carefully considered as part of the overall security strategy of the local network.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A router may include a firewall, VPN handling, and other security functions, or they may be handled by separate devices.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Routers also commonly perform network address translation, which restricts connections initiated from external connections but is not recognized as a security feature by all experts.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Some experts argue that open source routers are more secure and reliable than closed source routers because errors and potentially exploitable vulnerabilities are more likely to be discovered and addressed in an open-source environment.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Routers are also often distinguished on the basis of the network in which they operate.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A router in a local area network (LAN) of a single organization is called an *interior router*.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A router that is operated in the Internet backbone is described as *exterior router*.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] While a router that connects a LAN with the Internet or a wide area network (WAN) is called a *border router*, or *gateway router*.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Routers intended for ISP and major enterprise connectivity usually exchange routing information using the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Wi-Fi routers combine the functions of a router, switch and a wireless access point.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] They are typically devices with a small form factor, operating on the standard electric power supply for residential use.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Connected to the Internet as offered by an Internet service provider, they provide Internet access through Ethernet and Wi-Fi for home or office use.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The main purpose of a router is to connect multiple networks and forward packets destined either for directly attached networks or more remote networks.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A router is considered a layer-3 device because its primary forwarding decision is based on the information in the layer-3 IP packet, specifically the destination IP address.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] When a router receives a packet, it searches its routing table to find the best match between the destination IP address of the packet and one of the addresses in the routing table.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Once a match is found, the packet is encapsulated in the layer-2 data link frame for the outgoing interface indicated in the table entry.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A router typically does not look into the packet payload, but only at the layer-3 addresses to make a forwarding decision, plus optionally other information in the header for hints on, for example, quality of service (QoS).
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] For pure IP forwarding, a router is designed to minimize the state information associated with individual packets.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Once a packet is forwarded, the router does not retain any historical information about the packet.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The routing table itself can contain information derived from a variety of sources, such as a default or static routes that are configured manually, or dynamic entries from routing protocols where the router learns routes from other routers.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] A default route is one that is used to route all traffic whose destination does not otherwise appear in the routing table; it is common – even necessary – in small networks, such as a home or small business, where the default route simply sends all non-local traffic to the Internet service provider.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] The default route can be manually configured (as a static route); learned by dynamic routing protocols; or be obtained by DHCP.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Besides deciding to which interface a packet is forwarded, which is handled primarily via the routing table, a router also has to manage congestion when packets arrive at a rate higher than the router can process.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Three policies commonly used are tail drop, random early detection (RED), and weighted random early detection (WRED).
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Tail drop is the simplest and most easily implemented: the router simply drops new incoming packets once buffer space in the router is exhausted.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] RED probabilistically drops datagrams early when the queue exceeds a pre-configured portion of the buffer, until reaching a pre-determined maximum, when it drops all incoming packets, thus reverting to tail drop.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] WRED can be configured to drop packets more readily depending on the type of traffic.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Another function a router performs is traffic classification and deciding which packet should be processed first.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] This is managed through QoS, which is critical when Voice over IP is deployed, so as not to introduce excessive latency.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Yet another function a router performs is called policy-based routing, where special rules are constructed to override the rules derived from the routing table when a packet forwarding decision is made.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Some of the functions may be performed through an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) to avoid the overhead of scheduling CPU time to process the packets.
[src:network-on-chip/router-computing] Others may have to be performed through the CPU as these packets need special attention that cannot be handled by an ASIC.
